ity was the norm and conditions encouraged its practice. In his new introduction, Burg discusses the initial response to the book when it was published in 1983 and how our perspectives on all-male societies have since changed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMale homosexualityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy17th century. 0aMale homosexualityzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPiratesxSexual behaviorzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy17th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081471235140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814739228.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814739228/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles